ğŸ”¹ What is Component Scanning?
In Spring Boot (and Spring in general), Component Scanning is the process by which Spring automatically detects classes (like @Component, @Service, @Repository, @Controller) and creates beans for them in the Spring Application Context â€” so you donâ€™t need to configure them manually.

Think of it like:
ğŸ‘‰ Spring goes into the package you tell it, looks around for "special classes" (annotated ones), and says â€œOkay, Iâ€™ll manage this class for you as a bean.â€

ğŸ”¹ How It Works?
You put annotations on your classes:

@Component â†’ Generic bean

@Service â†’ Business logic layer bean

@Repository â†’ DAO / Database layer bean

@Controller or @RestController â†’ Web layer bean

Spring Boot automatically does component scanning starting from the package where your @SpringBootApplication class is located.

ğŸ”¹ Real-Time Example
Imagine you are building a shopping application:

1. Main Class
@SpringBootApplication
public class ShoppingApp {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(ShoppingApp.class, args);
    }
}
2. Service Layer
@Service
public class ProductService {
    public String getProduct() {
        return "Laptop";
    }
}
3. Controller Layer
@RestController
public class ProductController {
    
    private final ProductService productService;

    // Spring injects this automatically because of component scanning
    public ProductController(ProductService productService) {
        this.productService = productService;
    }

    @GetMapping("/product")
    public String getProduct() {
        return productService.getProduct();
    }
}
ğŸ”¹ What Happened Behind the Scenes?
Spring Boot started from ShoppingApp package.

It scanned all classes in the same package and sub-packages.

It found:

@Service â†’ created ProductService bean.

@RestController â†’ created ProductController bean.

When /product endpoint is called, Spring injected ProductService into ProductController automatically.

ğŸ”¹ Real-Life Analogy
Think of component scanning like a metal detector in an airport:

You (Spring) walk through the terminal (project package).

The detector (scanner) beeps whenever it finds a special item (annotated class).

Security (Spring) takes that item (class) and registers it so it can be used inside the airport system (Application Context).

ğŸ‘‰ Without component scanning, you would need to manually define beans in @Configuration classes using @Bean methods â€” which is tedious.

